title: For Sale:  AK-47 75-Round Drum ***Update***
postcontent:
Update:  I'm waiting to validate the country of origin.  If it's not worth what I'm asking I'll take the posting down.  I don't want to be "That Guy" on here.  I bought it from Sportsman's Guide last year, anyone know what they were selling?  

This is a NIB 75-round drum designed for use with an AK-47.  This drum loads from the back, comes with the original directions, and accommodates 7.62x39mm ammo.  

I’m not sure of the country of origin.  The instructions only list Century International Arms as the distributor and no country of origin.  It looks identical – to me – to the Romanian drums.  The rivets are in the same places and other details all appear the same.  Either way, I’m sure when you fill it with ammo it’ll go "Bang" seventy-five times followed by an audible, “Click”.  

This was purchased in 2012 and never used.  It sat forgotten about until last week when I wondered what was in the plain brown box and opened it.  I’m a bit of a traditionalist and prefer to fire from standard 30-round magazines and I don’t anticipate using it anytime soon.  So, it’s up for sale.  

I see these are all the way up to a ridiculous almost $300 on MN Armslist.  Homey don’t play that game.  I’m selling this for $175 which seems fair.  You can get them for as cheap as $160 on this site.  Mine is unfired / NIB and comes with the original directions.  I’m thinking that’s worth the extra $15.  Heck, if you want to go up to $200 I’ll throw in the first 75-rounds of AK ammo to fill the drum.  The extra $25 actually makes the ammo a few cents less than I paid for it.  

I don’t need to see a permit or require a DNA sample to purchase this.  It hasn’t come to that for magazines and drums… Yet.  

Keep your powder dry.

I've got a Ruger Mini-30 7.62x39 semi-automatic rifle. It's just like a Mini 14, except it shoots the AK round instead of the AR round. The AK round is for sure more powerful, and cheaper.

It's got the regular, NEW YORK LEGAL wood stock, void of a collapsible butt stock or a pistol grip, meaning the commie lawmakers won't call it an "assault weapon." This guy is just about as good as it gets in New York. It's a hell of a rifle, light and handy, but powerful enough to blast your way through a cinder block wall. If you've never seen one, it looks and comes apart like an M1 Carbine, but it shoots like an AK-47. I've put high quality American Winchester ammo through it, and I've put cheap Golden Tiger and Tula surplus ammo through it, and it eats it up. Steel cased ammo is no problem.

In addition, I also have a black ATI tactical stock. This item is a black stock built for the Mini 14, except I used a dremel to widen the magazine well to accommodate the Mini 30 magazines. It could use some smoothing down, but it works just fine. This stock has a pistol grip and telescoping stock, as well as side and top rails. The item must be sold SEPARATELY seeing as, once it is placed on the rifle, it makes the rifle become an "assault weapon." I would like to stress this again. This item is to be sold separately, but is included in this price. Since it itself is not a firearm, I could ship it. But it needs to be in two orders.

In addition to the extra stock, I have an Accu-Strut put on, and a 4x scope with its own rail. The scope rail is to be mounted on the rifle's sights. I have never mounted it as I am not much of a scope guy. I also have a flash suppressor, but unfortunately, the commies in New York don't think you should be able to have one, so it's not for sale. I'll have to get rid of it somehow else.

The rifle comes with a 5-round Ruger magazine that's only been used once or twice, and two 10-round aftermarket magazines that I normally use. It also comes with a bolt lock.
